  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">GRC-YRCS Primary Health Centres (Hajjah,Al Dhalee)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Since the escalation of violence in March 2015, the healthcare sector in Yemen has been unable to respond to the rising needs.
This intervention is a continuation of BRC&apos;s support to German Red Cross&apos;s in YRCS&apos;s health facilities in Yemen. It covers YRCS Health Centre and Emergency Obstetrics clinic in Hajjah, which has been supported by BRC since April 2016; and the extended support to the Al Dhalee Health Centre, which GRC has been supporting since 2019.
The project&apos;s overall objective is that conflict-affected people have access to emergency medical care and primary health care free of charge at YRCS health facilities. This will be achieved through the provision of drugs/medical supplies and supporting with operating and staff costs.
&#xC2;&#xA0;
Since April 2016, the British Red Cross (BRC) has been successful in funding the EmOC unit; securing &#xC2;&#xA3;30,000 from the Jersey Overseas Aid Committee (JOAC) in 2016 and &#xC2;&#xA3;140,000 from the Disasters Emergency Committee (DEC) (Feb- Dec 2018). Both contributions have supplemented BRC&#xE2;&#x20AC;&#x2122;s own appeal funds. 
&#xC2;&#xA0;In 2019 BRC has committed to continuing its support to EmOC with &#xC2;&#xA3;480,000 for a further 24 months until Feb 2021.This is a mixture of restricted funds secured from the Isle of Man government (&#xC2;&#xA3;81,989), and Volant (&#xC2;&#xA3;100,000), supplemented bv BRC&#xE2;&#x20AC;&#x2122;s own Emergency Appeal funds.
In 2021, BRC entered a new agreement with GRC to support an additional health centre in Al Dhalee.</narrative>
  </description>
